title.rendered: India vs Ireland, Women’s T20 World Cup 2023: Fantasy Team, Probable Playing XIs, Pitch Report & Fantasy Tips

content.rendered:
We have opted for a fantasy cricket team based on the recent performances, overall impact, and credit points.

Probable Playing XIs for India & Ireland

India: Shafali Verma, Smriti Mandhana, Jemimah Rodrigues, Harmanpreet Kaur (c), Richa Ghosh (wk), Shikha Pandey, Deepti Sharma, Pooja Vastrakar, Radha Yadav, Rajeshwari Gayakwad, Renuka Thakur Singh

Ireland: Amy Hunter, Gaby Lewis, Orla Prendergast, Laura Delany (c), Eimear Richardson, Louise Little, Mary Waldron (wk), Leah Paul, Arlene Kelly, Cara Murray, Jane Maguire

Pitch Report for St George’s Park, Gqeberha

Venue: St George’s Park, Gqeberha

(Based on the last three games)

1st innings average score: 129

2nd innings average score: 126

Wickets per innings: 5

Type: Good for batting

Wins

Batting 1st: 33%

Batting 2nd: 67%

Also Read:

Quetta vs Peshawar, Pakistan T20 League 2023 Fantasy Tips

Pakistan vs West Indies, Women’s T20 World Cup 2023 Fantasy Tips

Fantasy Tips of The Day

In the only game India played at St George’s Park, Smriti Mandhana (52 off 41) and Richa Ghosh (47* off 34) were the star batters.

Renuka Singh’s best figures (5 for 15) in the format have come at the very venue.

In the only game played between these teams, Radha Yadav turned out to be a power player for picking 3 for 25.

Gaby Lewis is the only Irish player to feature in the Best11 in four of the last five games. She, for that matter, has been in great form of late. In her last 10 outings, she has generated 30-run bonus four times and 50-run bonus twice.

Orla Prendergast made it to the Best11 in all three games of the tournament. Her 109 runs are the most for Ireland, in addition to taking a wicket.

Since her debut in June 2022, Arlene Kelly has picked the most wickets for Ireland: 24 wickets in 19 games.

Laura Delany has been generating points with both bat and ball of late. Her best score reads 32 and best figures are 3 for 20 on the tour.

In the last three games at the venue, 18 of 30 wickets belonged to pacers. The new ball especially troubled the batters.
